                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>Rev. S. M. Fleischman<lb/></p>
            <p>Dec. 13 1888.<lb/></p>
            <p>My dear sir&#44;<lb/></p>
            <p>In justice to myself and in obedience to a sense of duty&#44; I<lb/> must answer your note just received at some length.  It was due to you<lb/> that I should say what I knew to be the object of Mrs. Weiss&#39; request.  To<lb/> conceal it would have been to do violence to the rules that have guided<lb/> me through life&#44; and to act offensively toward one to whom was committed the<lb/> best interest of a Jewish Institution.  But you will permit me to say that<lb/> as a teacher of our people&#44; who will never limit himself in the discharge<lb/> of what he deems his religious obligations&#44; I could not refuse to comply<lb/> with Mrs W&#39;s wish.  Naturally you were to be consulted&#44; before her boy<lb/> should come to me for instruction in an observance which she evidently<lb/> values &#40;and which I have always followed&#45;&#45;crossed out&#41; but to withhold<lb/> my services when asked in sincerity of feelings&#44; I dared not.  It would be<lb/> arrogant on my part to discuss the importance of the ceremonial injunction<lb/> of the Phylacteries in a letter simply penned to place myself in a right<lb/> light.  I may regret that we differ&#44; the more so for reasons which your<lb/> clear understanding will interpret at once&#44; but as I disclaim any right to<lb/> act in the capacity of a public mentor&#44; I shall say nothing further.<lb/>  With kind regards&#44; and good wishes for the prosperity of the Home&#44;<lb/> I remain<lb/> Yours truly<lb/></p>
            </body>
    </text>
